Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Odd Rode, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","North Rode, Cheshire, England":"North Rode, Cheshire, England","Barthomley, Cheshire East district, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Barthomley, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1189–1265":"1189–1265","1183–1270":"1183–1270","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1230–1304":"1230–1304","1235–1310":"1235–1310","ABT 1235":"about 1235","1230":"1230","1183":"1183","1270":"1270","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1204":"1204","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1189":"1189","about 1204":"about 1204","1310":"1310","1265":"1265","1208":"1208","Dutton, Cheshire, England":"Dutton, Cheshire, England","Baddiley, Cheshire East, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Baddiley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Odd Rode, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Odd Rode, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","North Rode, Cheshire, England":"North Rode, Cheshire, England","Barthomley, Cheshire East district, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Barthomley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jordan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, French (mainly Alsace and Haute-Savoie), Polish, Czech, and Slovenian; Spanish and Hungarian (<b>Jordán</b>): from the Christian personal name or nickname <i>Jordan</i>. This is taken from the name of the river Jordan (Hebrew <i>Yarden</i>, a derivative of <i>yarad</i> ‘to go down’, i.e. to the Dead Sea). At the time of the Crusades it was a common practice for crusaders and pilgrims to bring back flasks of water from the river in which John the Baptist had baptized people, including Christ himself, and to use it in the christening of their own children. As a result <i>Jordan</i> became quite a common personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Giordano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Rocco, Antonio, Pasquale, Carmine, Vito, Domenic, Gaetano, Giuseppe, Sal, Santo.","Italian: from the personal name <i>Giordano</i>, an equivalent of   Jordan  ."]},{"name":"Jourdan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Dominique, Gabrielle, Henri, Lucien, Pierre, Raoul, Yves.","English: variant of   Jordan  .","French (mainly southern): variant of   Jourdain  , a cognate of 2 below."]},{"name":"Jourdain","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Henri, Pierre, Fritz, Hans, Jacques, Rommel.","French, Breton (mainly Finistère), and West Indian (mainly Haiti, also Martinique and Dominican Republic): from the French personal name <i>Jourdain</i>, an equivalent of   Jordan  .","English (London, Derbyshire): French-influenced variant of   Jordan  ; compare 1 above."]},{"name":"Jordison","meanings":["English (North Yorkshire, Durham, and Northumberland): from a Middle English pet form, <i>Jordi</i>, of the male personal name   Jordan   + <i>-son</i>, or directly from a phonetic shortening of <i>Jordanson</i>."]},{"name":"Jorden","meanings":["English: variant of   Jordan  .","North German (mainly <b>Jörden</b>): probably a variant of   Jordan  . Compare   Yerden   and   Yerdon  ."]},{"name":"Judd","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Judde</i>, <i>Jutte</i>, a pet form of   Jordan  .","German: variant of   Jude  ."]},{"name":"Jorda","meanings":["Catalan (<b>Jordà</b>): from the personal name <i>Jordà</i> (see   Jordan  )."]},{"name":"Jerden","meanings":["English: from a variant of the personal name <i>Jurdon</i>, an old form of   Jordan  ."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]},{"name":"Jordon","meanings":["English: variant of   Jordan  ."]}]},{"name":"Cecily","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecilie","meanings":["Medieval vernacular English form of   Cecilia ."]},{"name":"Cicely","meanings":["Variant of   Cecily .  This was a common form of the name in the Middle Ages, and in the 20th century was well known as the name of the British actress and singer  Cicely Courtneidge  (  1893–1980 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":26,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":35,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":70,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Cecily Jordan was born in 1189, in Barthomley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Thomas de Rode in 1208, in Baddiley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1265, in North Rode, Cheshire, England, at the age of 76."},"et":{"1189–1265":"1189